{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510478","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510478"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:30:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:30:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11572"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11572","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11572"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.44,0.17,0.1,0.23]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4201"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45920"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4201","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4201"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11572"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30864"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"446"},{"type":"tags","id":"4051"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5432"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7197"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11816"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44280"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45920","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/45920"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously healthy 30-year-old man presents with a four-day history of easy fatigue and bone pains. He gives no medical history except for a recent urinary tract infection one week ago for which he was prescribed ciprofloxacin. On examination, his blood pressure is 134/74 mmHg, pulse 92 /min, respiratory rate 16 /min and temperature 37.30C. He looks pale and jaundiced. There is no lymphadenopathy, hepatomegaly or splenomegaly. Cardiac and chest examination are normal. His investigations show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 73 g/L [115-155]\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMCV 101 fL [76-100]\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets 254 x 10^9/L [150-450]\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count 10.2 x 10^9/L [4.0-10.0]\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPeripheral blood smear is shown (Image)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal Bilirubin 98 \u03bcmol/L [3 -22]\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELactate Dehydrogenase 925 IU/L [100-250]\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaptoglobin \u0026lt;0.10 g/L [0.5-2.5]\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDirect antiglobulin test (DAT) negative\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pyruvate kinase deficiency","Glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase deficiency","Hereditary spherocytosis","Sickle cell disease","Autoimmune haemolysis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has presented with acute intravascular haemolysis (anaemia, hyperbilirubinaemia, high LDH, and low haptoglobin level), high MCV (due to reticulocytosis) and bite cells in a peripheral blood smear after exposure to oxidative stress (ciprofloxacin). These features are consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003EGlucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase (G6PD) deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E. The diagnosis requires testing for G6PD deficiency; however it is important to remember that it may be falsely negative during the haemolytic attack because older erythrocytes with a higher enzyme deficiency have been haemolysed while young erythrocytes and reticulocytes have normal or near-normal enzyme activity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPyruvate kinase deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E presents with chronic haemolysis with variable severity, from fully compensated anaemia to lifelong transfusion-dependent anaemia. A blood film shows poikilocytosis and distorted \u2018prickle\u2019 cells. In this patient, the presentation of acute haemolytic attack with a history of oxidative stress (drug) and bite cells makes G6PD deficiency the more likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn \u003Cstrong\u003Ehereditary spherocytosis\u003C/strong\u003E, patients are usually asymptomatic or present with mild to moderate haemolytic anaemia, splenomegaly and gall stones. Spherocytes are characteristically seen on peripheral blood smear. The diagnosis needs more specific tests (osmotic fragility and eosin maleimide assay).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESickle cell disease\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by intermittent vaso-occlusion and haemolysis. Sickle cells are characteristically present in the blood smear. The diagnosis is confirmed by the presence of HbS in haemoglobin electrophoresis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutoimmune haemolysis\u003C/strong\u003E may have a similar presentation; however, in most cases, peripheral smear shows microspherocytes and the antiglobulin test is expected to be positive.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["G6PD deficiency may present as acute haemolytic attacks following oxidative stress, congenital non spherocytic haemolytic anaemia, or neonatal jaundice.","In G6PD, peripheral blood smear may show ghost cells, bite cells, and/or Heinz body (on supravital stain).","G6PD assay may be falsely negative in acute crisis when reticulocyte count is high (reticulocytes have high G6PD levels) and it should be repeated after the attack."],"references":["Haley K. Congenital Hemolytic Anemia. Med Clin North Am [Internet]. 2017; 101(2):361\u201374."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30864"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11572"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17494"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17494","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17494"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8437ae1d-f67b-485e-9db1-b1eda16e1468.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8437ae1d-f67b-485e-9db1-b1eda16e1468.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":404}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30864","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/30864"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-05-23T22:27:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-05-23T22:27:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4201"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45920"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"r